cs.IT, cs.LG, cs.DS, cs.SI, cs.AI. 

The paper deals with clustering and information theory, which are both relevant to several sub-categories in computer science. However, the focus on mutual information as a cost function and the use of convexity properties suggest that cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely sub-category. The use of clustering algorithms and optimization techniques also make cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) likely sub-categories. The paper's focus on co-clustering and pairwise clustering problems suggests cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as another possible sub-category. Finally, the use of hard clusters as a relaxation of the combinatorial problem suggests cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as a possible sub-category.
